Reamer's girlfriend from Three Forks, MT dropped him off at his apartment on Wilder St. in Helena, Sunday, March 27, 1994. He had spent the week-end with her and their young son. She claimed there was an unknown male at his apartment when she dropped him off. The next morning (Monday, 28th)the girlfriend and "surrogate" mother both claimed to have spoken to Reamer on the phone before he left for class at Carroll College. The neighbor remembered seeing him on the night of the 27th, but he didn't come over for breakfast the morning of the 28th as planned.
Reamer was initially reported missing on April 4, 1994, but was last seen on March 27, 1994. Items remaining behind in his apt. were his all his personal belongings including his billfold, bicycle, and school books. His vehicle remained parked outside the apt. His favorite cowboy hat was missing.
Reamer was under state supervision at the time of his disappearance in connection with a 1992 assault that occurred in Manhatten, MT. Reamer was bi-polar and was prescribed medication, but was off it at the time of his disappearance. He had alcohol and drug use in his history and was facing a return to jail on his original felony assault charge after an arrest for DUI several months before his disappearance.
Reamer used to work on fishing boats up in Unalaska, Alaska and construction in Helena until he injured his back. Reamer had a distinct Native American tattoo on his upper right arm with the words "Makah Nation" encompassing a circular design surrounded by serpents and having two feathers hanging down. The tattoo had alot of yellow, red, and green in it.
